  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The study titled \"Coordinated distributed experiments in ecology do not consistently reduce heterogeneity in effect size\" presents important findings on the variability of ecological responses. Published in Oikos in 2024, it has already garnered attention with five citations across respected journals such as PLoS Biology and Ecology Letters.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work by Julia Bebout and Jeremy W. Fox explores the dynamics of coordinated distributed experiments within ecological research. Their findings emphasize that such experiments may not consistently lead to the expected reduction in heterogeneity regarding effect sizes. This crucial insight has potential implications for ecological theory and practice, inviting further exploration and refinement of experimental methodologies.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">With five citations to date, including mentions in prominent ecological journals like Ecography and Ecology and Evolution, the article demonstrates its relevance within the academic community. The overlap of citations from multiple countries, including the United States, Germany, and Canada, highlights the broader geographical impact and interest in the authors\u2019 findings.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Additionally, the data associated with this study is hosted in the Dryad Dataset repository, showcasing the authors' commitment to open data practices. This commitment facilitates ongoing scholarly engagement and supports future inquiries in this vital area of ecology, allowing other researchers to build upon their findings effectively.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In conclusion, the study has initiated an important dialogue among ecologists, as reflected in its citations. As researchers continue to engage with these insights, the narrative surrounding the effectiveness of coordinated experiments in ecology is evolving, potentially informing best practices for experimental design in future ecological research.</p>",
